commit_message:
Remove unneeded definitions of Python Source Code Encoding

PEP 0263 (http://legacy.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0263/) is not
used anywhere else and should be removed when it's not needed.

Change-Id: I8c70ed26ccd416bb2e250ea1ebe5bd5014307966

commit_message:
Calculate a suitable column width for positional arguments

Overwrite the method add_arguments in the class
OpenStackHelpFormatter to calculate a suitable columnt width
(max_help_position) for the positional arguments.

commit_message:
use /usr/bin/env python instead of /usr/bin/python

The usage of /usr/bin/env ensures that the first interpreter
found in the environment's $PATH variable is used. This should
be preferred.

Change-Id: Iee0fe865ab66e9510e48965458239da35e0806f1

commit_message:
Pass object to policy when finding fields to strip

During the evaluation of fields to strip in responses to list
operations, pass also the first object in the list to the
policy engine.
This will avoid errors in policy evaluation if during
an upgrade from icehouse policy.json was not updated to remove
attribute-level policies dependent on resource values.

Closes-Bug: #1323715

Change-Id: Iaa6ed3bbf4a07ce0b614a4197cabdfa1cb36d427
(cherry picked from commit 2bd97d205b98292be709b0257bda5fc489eb643a)

[{'created': '2014-09-02 19:47:02.000000000', 'message': "Perform policy checks only once on list responses

The policy engine is currently being called for every attribute
of every resource to be returned by a list response. This is
harming the API performance; moreover such a high number of checks
is also unnecessary.

This patch therefore slightly changes the API logic so that list
response first determine the list of attributes which should be
returned querying the policy engine and then use this list for
all resource items to be returned.

To this aim a few methods in base.py needed to be refactored.
This patch also removes the routine check_if_exists from policy.py
and the related PolicyNotFound exception.

Finally, this patch also removes unnecessary admin_or_owner rules
when applied to attributes. This kind of rule indeed has no effect
anyway because of Neutron's ownership checks. The rules were removed
because this change won't allow anymore for having attribute-level
policies whose evaluation result depends on the resource value.

Implements blueprint faster-list-responses

Change-Id: I21b8273add5d5984f512ad94af5a99cf0b0a5d93

commit_message:
Perform policy checks only once on list responses

The policy engine is currently being called for every attribute
of every resource to be returned by a list response. This is
harming the API performance; moreover such a high number of checks
is also unnecessary.

This patch therefore slightly changes the API logic so that list
response first determine the list of attributes which should be
returned querying the policy engine and then use this list for
all resource items to be returned.

To this aim a few methods in base.py needed to be refactored.
This patch also removes the routine check_if_exists from policy.py
and the related PolicyNotFound exception.

Finally, this patch also removes unnecessary admin_or_owner rules
when applied to attributes. This kind of rule indeed has no effect
anyway because of Neutron's ownership checks. The rules were removed
because this change won't allow anymore for having attribute-level
policies whose evaluation result depends on the resource value.

Implements blueprint faster-list-responses

Change-Id: I21b8273add5d5984f512ad94af5a99cf0b0a5d93
(cherry picked from commit 9b2b5e1482ebec818556946230066984bf647186)

This patch enables host I/O cache for the VMs created by the labs
scripts.

Without host I/O cache, occasional VM filesystem corruption occured on
two out of three host systems when we started taking snapshots after
every service install on the controller VM. Typically, the affected
script would just hang. The issue is somewhat elusive: it occured only
on two out of three test hosts, and the longest observed streak of
correct controller VM builds in a row was 16 (number 17 ended with

'}]
commit_message:
labs: enable host I/O cache

This patch enables host I/O cache for the VMs created by the labs
scripts.

Without host I/O cache, occasional VM filesystem corruption occured on
two out of three host systems when we started taking snapshots after
every service install on the controller VM. Typically, the affected
script would just hang. The issue is somewhat elusive: it occured only
on two out of three test hosts, and the longest observed streak of
correct controller VM builds in a row was 16 (number 17 ended with
filesystem corruption).

With host I/O cache enabled, 125 builds were successful and none failed.

Change-Id: Ib36f44fdbf9366ef781df82f225e5ac8c5bb678f

commit_message:
Calculate a suitable column width for positional arguments

Overwrite the method add_arguments in the class
OpenStackHelpFormatter to calculate a suitable columnt width
(max_help_position) for the positional arguments.

This should be preferred instead of overwritting the __init__ method
to overwrite the default value of the max_help_position parameter.

Change-Id: I659bf0d6ee9c5b8273f061e4462de2b04dd8363e

commit_message:
Use /usr/bin/env python instead of /usr/bin/python

The usage of /usr/bin/env ensures that the first interpreter
found in the environment's $PATH variable is used. This should
be preferred.

Change-Id: I963daef43220c2f153c84bb12ce482ef129ed6f6

commit_message:
except ImportError when importing cPickle on Python3

cPickle is not available with Python3. With Python3 the standard
version should be imported.

Change-Id: I644abe172efe902bee2770a142da82d5d82755a9

commit_message:
use strutils.to_slug() instead of utils.slugify()

Oslo provides a function, to_slug() in strutils that is substantially
similar to slugify() provided in utils by python-troveclient. Remove
slugify() and use to_slug() instead.

Change-Id: I4ee683174c3f89bfad285dc689ef5c1a41070dba
Closes-Bug: #1266127

commit_message:
Remove unneeded definitions of Python Source Code Encoding

I think PEP 0263 (http://legacy.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0263/) is
not used anywhere else and so it should be removed when it's not
needed.

Change-Id: Id7dbc11e9024989c992f276c5cc459131d810b46

commit_message:
add hacking checks for translation support

This patch adds a new hacking check (N320) that ensures that
all log messages, except debug ones, have translations.

This patch adds a new hacking check (N319) that ensures
all debug log messages don't have translations.

Change-Id: I492847143c37ab26571685949158a7157283e851

commit_message:
replace string format arguments with function parameters

There are files containing string format arguments inside
logging messages. Using logging function parameters should
be preferred.

Change-Id: Icea226b8c9dd79e9004e7cd9dcabe4237789f5b8
Closes-Bug: #1320931

commit_message:
replace string format arguments with function parameters

There are files containing string format arguments inside
logging messages. Using logging function parameters should
be preferred.

Change-Id: I35becdc6ced7c9bb9cd137dab3f28774b67e0e35
Closes-Bug: #1321754

commit_message:
replace iterator.next() with next(iterator)

According to https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Python3 iterator.next()
should be replaced with next(iterator).

Change-Id: I2aa4d8810c28f345d2e0a3c721d68b99ff3b225c

commit_message:
debug level logs should not be translated

According to the OpenStack translation policy, available at
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/LoggingStandards, debug messages
should not be translated. Like mentioned in several changes in
Nova by garyk this is to help prioritize log translation.

Change-Id: I00ec1a57e0f0cbe8736ee768e267251ed6afe5f2
Closes-Bug: #1317851

commit_message:
Decouple Nested Stacks from parents

Initial draft of idea for interim scalability improvement for
scenarios where a large heirarchy is of nested stacks is deployed,
if we can decouple the nested stacks from their parents, then we
should be able to more effectively spread workload over multiple
engines or workers, whereas currently the entire tree of stacks
must be processed by one engine.

specs bp decouple-nested

Change-Id: Ic6e955733030c80982221338a6d99c9c67cf064c

commit_message:
WIP: replace dict.iteritems() with six.iteritems(dict)

According to https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Python3 dict.iteritems()
should be replaced with six.iteritems(dict).

Change-Id: I784f75aeef79558d49f9996c41ca627be4d99903

commit_message:
set default auth_strategy to keystone

Like in change Ife63dc7ab680fcf0588d95c98fc9f29901485c64 for Nova
the default for auth_strategy should be keystone instead of noauth.

Change-Id: I1712484f3743b083a9b523f9beaefdc7da126cb4

commit_message:
Add rhel7-rdo-icehouse element

This element is for building RHEL7 images using rdo packages from
the Fedora Icehouse repository.

This patch relies on the following patches from tripleo-image-elements:
I8c35d55e7cffb358613436d87ee67e6484533bbb
I092f5f2326c424694cf34578b7fca7e2a3f4d4d5

Change-Id: I2bd9751e2678a1388fafde92ab247fab301575d8

commit_message:
add repr for event objects

When an event object gets dumped in a stack trace, because there
is no __repr__ of it, we don't get any details about what it was.
Add a __repr__ to all the event objects so that we can get this
information on a fail.

Closes-Bug: #1357063

Change-Id: I9a62a4348871b748c53b7354ad1b821fe987127d

commit_message:
make lifecycle event logs more clear

Instead of logging integers in a cryptic way, log the human
readable strings for VM event state transitions. Also use the
existing instance_uuid port of the logger instead of putting that
separately into our log message.

Partial-Bug: #1357063

Change-Id: I96c39ad4494aa06a8dd5bd942c669a16836a8b9c
(cherry picked from commit 79c8bee9be7b6cf4e9fd3365a162f93a2b014bb5)

commit_message:
Maint: neutronclient exceptions from a more appropriate module

When nova wants to use neutronclient exceptions, it should import
neutronclient.common.exceptions, but there are some cases they import
nova.network.neutronv2, which indeed can import neutronclient exceptions,
but may confuse people. This patch fixes them.

Change-Id: Ief388fc631d18c709a629980143d53f240a2ed2b

commit_message:
DO NOT MERGE: run worlddump at end of devstack

Run worldump at end of devstack to see how much memory processes are
taking. Compare this to the ps we collect at the end of a run to see how
much memory usage is startup overhead.

Change-Id: I64e81fe363ba121f1cdf355c6af46b33ec5a9b6f

commit_message:
Fix metadata agent's auth info caching

metadata agent does not implement auth info cache correctly but
retrieves from keystone every time

Change-Id: Ifc1f580185d7600b48aaf80d112fc80e0c4253f2
Closes-bug: #1365352

(4 comments)

I would like to see this change entirely revert I6a9e2977b275e96dcf01c4df90a33169c42287d6 , since the _default_timeout  value that it added is no longer required now that the problem has been found to be an uncanceled eventlet timeout.  The only place timeout is used is in neutron.tests.functional.agent.linux.test_ovsdb_monitor.SimpleInterfaceMonitor, and it should be extended (say to 60s) there in the call to start() rather than requiring a modification to the runtime class.'}, {'account_id': 2035, 'date': '2014-09-04 09:15:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 12444, 'date': '2014-09-04 10:23:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(6 comments)

@Maru, I'm fine with reverting the change request you mentioned, but I think it will increase non-deterministic errors. The default timeout used right now at the gate is 10 seconds. Reverting that patch as a whole will set that timeout to 5, making the non-deterministic failures to pop up even more often.

I advise changing the timeout to 20 seconds (lower than 30 used by ovsdb monitor). This will not change the base code heavily as my first patchset proposed, but also help eliminating the non-deterministic timeouts."}, {'account_id': 12444, 'date': '2014-09-04 10:56:33.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 2035, 'date': '2014-09-04 11:01:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Fix leftover Timeout effecting most eventlet calls

When registering a new eventlet.timeout.Timeout object, eventlet
automatically starts a timer for most (if not all) future eventlet
calls. Normally, eventlet codes do not hold a timeout unless such a
timeout is used or a specific timeout length is specified through
the API, but once a Timeout object is initialized, it is left there
unless canceled.

This change fixes an un-canceled Timeout which causes some
functional tests to fail, reintroduces a fix for bug #1358206,
which was written prior to discovering the uncanceled timeout, and
increases the timeout of a test that depended on this timeout.

Closes-bug: #1358206
Related-bug: #1364171
Change-Id: I1bfc5af6917c525894eecd8b477d787763edbd02

commit_message:
Fix compute_driver and scheduler_host_manager in install-guide

This patch updates the install-guide to use the Ironic driver in the
Nova tree instead of the one in the Ironic tree, as I am sure the
the one in Ironic's tree is about to be deleted.

Change-Id: Idd526f8b36eee3501e3a955414c419150285993b

Skip the contents of /tmp/ when creating tarballs with the results of
debootstrap, as that directory contains just ccache cache (and in
general temporary files).

Small (positive) side effect is that deboostrap tarballs gets slightly
smaller, something like 2-3 MB less.

Change-Id: Ib4adf3dc908f02deed408bf9188f032767eeb2bb
'}]
commit_message:
debian: exclude contents of /tmp from debootstrap tarballs

Skip the contents of /tmp/ when creating tarballs with the results of
debootstrap, as that directory contains just ccache cache (and in
general temporary files).

Small (positive) side effect is that deboostrap tarballs gets slightly
smaller, something like 2-3 MB less.

Change-Id: Ib4adf3dc908f02deed408bf9188f032767eeb2bb

commit_message:
Add posibillity to use different types in task parameters

 * It is possible to use: null as None, true as True,
   false as False, int and list data types

Change-Id: I61ce00f2af2387fa397115e7e5a0413d11a0f22b

commit_message:
Translator functions cleanup part 4

This part fixes ironic/api, ironic/cmd, ironic/tests folders.

Some modules use _ function for log translation, even when the
translated string is passed to e.g. LOG.warn function. This patch
fixes it, using translator functions appropriate for corresponding
log levels. Translator functions, imported from
ironic.openstack.common.gettextutils are now imported from
ironic.common.i18n. Translator functions are imported the same way
across all modules. All places that are changed conform to
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.i18n/guidelines.html

Partial-bug: #1364813

Change-Id: I92e5f0d50c3b507080fb95e81274a241558ce526

commit_message:
Removed admin_user from benchmark.runners.base

Before this patch, an endpoint with admin credentials
was passed in to runner. This change makes the
architecture of Rally much cleaner, removing one
dependency in code.

Change-Id: I9637584c51429b2f95995fe07287b80118ceb761

commit_message:
Initialize metadata definitions catalog

This patch copies all files from /etc/metadefs to
/etc/glance/metadefs and calls glance-manage db_load_metadefs
after successful database migration. This covers whole
process of initializing the metadata catalog.

Change-Id: I2ffd19bf543708b42229ef78dd17ee317f58e6ad
Implements: blueprint glance-metadata-definitions-support
Co-Authored-By: Travis Tripp <travis.tripp@hp.com>

[{'created': '2014-09-08 14:53:53.000000000', 'message': "Too many if clauses in the _clean_incoming_headers and the
_clean_outgoing_headers routines of the tempurl module

Too many if clauses make code complicated. For more pythonic, you'd
better to use the for ... else clause instead of them.

Fix Bug #1363125

Change-Id: I837235ecb08dd912e56cdfb363c4b4a6cc053e7d
"}]
commit_message:
Too many if clauses in the _clean_incoming_headers and the
_clean_outgoing_headers routines of the tempurl module

Too many if clauses make code complicated. For more pythonic, you'd
better to use the for ... else clause instead of them.

Fix Bug #1363125

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

Index.html fix for startpanel command

Slight fix to horizon/conf index.html template. This is to fix the
"TemplateDoesNotExist" error arising from the incorrect template.

Closes-Bug: 1325099

driver that can cause messages to be reclaimed. The problem was that
between getting a list of "active" messages, and setting watch on

commit_message:
Fix messages getting reclaimed in the Redis driver

A race condition was discovered during smoke testing of the Redis
driver that can cause messages to be reclaimed. The problem was that
between getting a list of "active" messages, and setting watch on
them, they could be claimed by another process without the first
process being notified.

This patch gaurds against the race condition by moving the query for
active messages to execute after the watch has been set. In this way,
if another process commits a claim in the meantime, the first process
will be notified so that it can try again with a new batch of active
messages.

Change-Id: I27a7e88ef0c3f9f8b1c5e653caec0fc503905e13
Closes-Bug: #1367033

commit_message:
Do not reschedule FlavorDiskTooSmall exceptions

If one boots an image which has a disk size that's larger then the
allowed size in the flavor an exception previously was thrown on the
compute node. This caused the instance to be rescheduled (over and over
without *EVER* stopping). Each time the instance was rescheduled it
repulls down the disk image. This patch ensures an instance is not reschedule
if FlavorDiskTooSmall is raised.

There is a check to prevent this from occuring on nova-api but it uses the
compressed size image size instead of the actual size. Unfortunately, glance
doesn't seem to provide a way to get this data via the api and the only way to
determine the disk size is to fetch the disk locally.

This patch provides only a work around for the reschedule bug.

Change-Id: Iff45894d69650073ee6ed8fc8df7c959d2b3ac70
Partial-bug: 1325670

commit_message:
Add new enable-packages-install element

This element will set the install types to package for
a specified set of elements (see readme for full list).
This element is for convenience until diskimage-builder
is updated to global set package installs.

Change-Id: I8c35d55e7cffb358613436d87ee67e6484533bbb

commit_message:
Fixed bug in config file poll_time parameter

Previously, the poll_time of each datasource could not be set
in the config file because the config read the value in as a string,
and the datasource driver didn't convert it to an int.   Thus setting
the poll_time in the config file caused an error in the driver.

This change casts the poll_time to an int on initialization.

Change-Id: I0fe1db536f7e91948a59c6f80a87baa896fa7fcd

commit_message:
Use ironic's bash-completion for CLI commands

This removes the list of ironic subcommands. Ironic now has a bash-completion
subcommand, and that will be used instead, to generate the list of subcommands.

Change-Id: I5adcbc8f755f6031ddc122205203ccfcedcf7a15
Closes-Bug: #1367333

commit_message:
Remove the token id from V2 token body

For support of PKI tokens, the persisted V2 token body should not
contain the token id itself. This is because the token body is used
as the basis to hash/sign for the PKI token id.

Change-Id: I468336b5fe881695f8112efa4e5a5a55ccba4805
Closes-Bug: #1328067

commit_message:
Fix another_role variable for swift

An error occurs because ANOTHER_ROLE variable in lib/swift is not set.
This patch gets and sets the value to another_role variable.

Change-Id: I9d67ce243eb6bb42ed7e3522ef816295847d48fa
Closes-Bug: #1363884

Could you quantify "remote privilege escalation exploit" for me Steven? If you are saying that a template writer can execute scripts with any privileges on the heat engine box, then I would be interested to know how you see that happening.

Yes, I believe it would be possible for untrusted code to run on the heat engine node possibly cracking the entire infrastructure.  I am not concerned with VM security with the patch.

Not being a chef expert, I don't have any way to provide proof that this is possible (or would -2 the change:) but it seems possible by looking at the code.'}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Could this please be un-abandoned with the lastest version deployed to rackspace?  That would make it easier to figure out how to migrate it to software-config'}, {'account_id': 5494, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

New patchset patch-id matches previous patchset, but commit message has changed.'}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Thanks for the pointer to the BP; that helped to understand.

So overall, especially from an interface perspective (with interface I mean e.g. the resource properties) that looks like a good start. Also seems to fit to a design idea we've been discussing at the design summit (I'm going to write something down and post it early next week).

So thoughts on possible enhancements:

It would be good to allow also getting output results from a chef execution, so should a list of name-value pairs (to make it generic) be added to the attributes schema of the resource?

The ssh-ing into the server surely works, but I think some people do not like it. Seems like doing bootstrapping via cloud-init and passing metadata via the metadata server is cristalizing as an option to invoke software config tools."}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

Look forward to seeing the remote in-instance stuff.'}, {'account_id': 7395, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Restored'}, {'account_id': 7395, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Will try to get that done today Steve.'}, {'account_id': 7395, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Work In Progress

Thomas Spatzier: I linked a blueprint which should help to explain what I am trying to do here. Any feedback is appreciated.'}, {'account_id': 7395, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Could you quantify "remote privilege escalation exploit" for me Steven? If you are saying that a template writer can execute scripts with any privileges on the heat engine box, then I would be interested to know how you see that happening. Otherwise, if you are talking about executing code with heightened priviliges on the spun up compute instance, then I would disagree. Running chef will most likely require root privilidges anyway, so there is not much we can do to lock that down. I am working to refactor this code to download cookbooks, and do as much work as possible on the spun up compute instance, which would relieve most of those problems (that could possibly happen on the heat engine node). The next area of concern I think is running these commands over ssh. I would argue that regardless of if you use ssh or the metadata service to run scripts, you are still opening up the spun up instance to the possibility of an exploit. Having the ability to perform updates via chef is going to be a great asset of this resource, and I don't see how using the metadata service vs the ssh service would make this any more secure. Also, we are still working on getting the metadata service on our cloud here at Rackspace, so ssh is the best way for now.'}, {'account_id': 7395, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

[{'created': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'message': 'Chef solo resource

Allow a compute resource to be bootstrapped with chef-solo. This
resource uses berkshelf/librarian-chef to download cookbooks,
then knife solo to write databags, roles, and a node json
file on the heat-engine node, and synchronizes them onto the
compute instance. Next chef-solo is called (via knife bootstrap).

Change-Id: I951814b23a0a99927fea08fa02c1157525c7604a

'}, {'created': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'message': 'Chef solo resource

commit_message:
Chef solo resource

Allow a compute resource to be bootstrapped with chef-solo. This
resource has two options for downloading cookbooks:

1). berkshelf/librarian-chef can be installed on the specified host,
allowing a Berksfile/Cheffile to be included with cookbook download
locations.

2). A "kitchen" can be specified which is a git url containing all
required cookbooks.

chef-solo is installed on the host via the Opscode omnibus installer,
the cookbooks are installed on the host, any databags, node files,
roles, etc... are created on the host, and chef-solo is called.

Change-Id: I951814b23a0a99927fea08fa02c1157525c7604a
Implements: blueprint chef-solo-resource

subject: Mask passwords in exceptions and error messages
messages: [{'account_id': 9311, 'date': '2014-09-09 20:19:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 9311, 'date': '2014-09-09 20:55:16.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned\n\nWrong cherry-pick'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-09 20:19:44.000000000', 'message': 'Mask passwords in exceptions and error messages

When a ProcessExecutionError is thrown by processutils.execute(), the
exception may contain information such as password. Upstream
applications that just log the message (as several appear to do) could
inadvertently expose these passwords to a user with read access to the
log files. It is therefore considered prudent to invoke
strutils.mask_password() on the command, stdout and stderr in the
exception.

Cherry-pick from review.openstack.org/109417
Cherry-pick from review.openstack.org/116763
Partial-Bug: #1343604

Conflicts:
	cinder/openstack/common/processutils.py

Change-Id: Ife45263abbff2074219e163fe2055dd57b354dff
'}]
commit_message:
Mask passwords in exceptions and error messages

When a ProcessExecutionError is thrown by processutils.execute(), the
exception may contain information such as password. Upstream
applications that just log the message (as several appear to do) could
inadvertently expose these passwords to a user with read access to the
log files. It is therefore considered prudent to invoke
strutils.mask_password() on the command, stdout and stderr in the
exception.

Fabio'}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2014-08-26 15:06:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Fabio. the main reason i ask is because if this patch goes in before the normalisation patch, i'll have to essentially destroy this entire patch and recreate it just to rebase the patch.  it'd be good to know beforehand if the performance is still relevant with the normalise resource patch and hopefully have this dependent on that.

i'd like to minimise the complexity of migration script if we intend on both patches going in... if there's an issue with normalisation patch, i'd like to know that as well."}, {'account_id': 3012, 'date': '2014-09-01 09:31:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-09-02 01:48:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

can anyone verify the performance gains? not really important that it's specifically 9x and 2.58x gains... just curious what everyone else is getting... because i got ~2.9% speed improvement.

am i doing something wrong? see https://review.openstack.org/#/c/111313/ for how i'm testing. 2.9% is  a lot different from 900% and 258% gains...

a soft minus0 on this since i'm not sure how much performance gain we really get"}, {'account_id': 12637, 'date': '2014-09-02 03:02:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

I am surprised you only see ~2% gains since we are adding an index that directly impacts the performance of the sub-query that is doing max(id) grouped by meter_id, project_id. I believe we both were on same page that "explain plan" without this new index does a full table scan for that sub-query.

Can you take a look at the explain plan for the meter-list query?

Again as I mentioned in other related post the main parameters like database, OS influences the results a lot. So we as a community have to decided on a standard setup to do these tests.'}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-09-02 03:25:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

yes, i'd expect a performance boost as well (even though we already index meter) which is why i asked what test steps were  so i could verify. i would assume os/database selection would have some level of variance in performance but i would think the difference would be at most tens of percents... not hundreds of percent"}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-09-02 10:53:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

" would assume os/database selection would have some level of variance"

Unfortunately the differences in query planner and index management between MySQL 5.5 and (MySQL 5.6 & MariaDB 5.5) is sizable and can have huge impact on some queries. I don't know if that's the case here, but unless we are testing with the exact same version of database engine we're not going to know.

My expectation is that the additional index will only make significant difference on mysql 5.5.

Unless we are concerned about the size cost of the additional index, then it seems worthwhile having it in place _if_ it has a positive impact on any of the usual databases.

It's relatively easy for me to do some testing with mariadb, please ping me on irc (cdent) if that would be useful.'}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-09-02 14:38:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

i don't know if this is a result of ceilometer-api service overhead but i get similar results using postgres 9.3.5... i did see a 5% bump for resource-list...

is it possible to get access to your cloud instance?"}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-09-02 17:56:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

chris did some performance tests and linked here: https://tank.peermore.com/tanks/cdent-rhat/DatabasePerfTest

it lists the methodology and such. i think it's a good start and we can see if we there's anything we should be tweaking"}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-09-09 20:47:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Code-Review-2

let's abandon this as it's been merged into bigger-data-sql patch.

thanks for the work Srinivas!"}, {'account_id': 12637, 'date': '2014-09-09 20:49:28.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Merged with https://review.openstack.org/#/c/111313/'}]

commit_message:
Get meters query performance improvements using index

Added a index for meter_id and resource_id on the sample table
This gives a 9x performance improvements for mysql v5.5 and 2.58x
improvement for Mysql v5.6.

Closes-Bug: #1320257

Change-Id: I9af13eb5a138f5748266170efe13ad60cb3e18a3

messages:

Everyone has a different experience with SQLite database files. Hence, this step periodically comes and goes from the installation guide. I think we should keep it for completeness. However, it may work better as a note than a step. If so, this patch (or another) should address all cases in the guide.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-09 17:37:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

I installed the Juno milestone package and it doesn't create the SQLite database file. However, this could change by release. In the grand scheme of things, we only remove this file to prevent services with misconfigured database keys from starting up and appearing to operate, but using the default SQLite database that causes problems later. A note makes more sense than removal."}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2014-09-09 19:01:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I think it's sufficient to use rm -f instead of rm. commit_message:
Respect user_id_attribute when building user

When translating an ldap response into a user object, set the id based
off of the value of self.id_attr, instead of just always using
commonName/cn.

Change-Id: Ib13b4b91d07ee0a703a5bacca915259e04263f78
Closes-Bug: 1254849

commit_message:
Update forms for bootstrap-datepicker 1.3.1

When bootstrap-datepicker is updated to 1.3.1,
this patch must be applied to fix a couple
of straightforward bugs. The datepicker patch
is: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/116866/

commit_message:
Ensure designate-api has policy initialized

We create a new WSGIService class, which inherits from both
the base designate Service class, and the openstack-common
wsgi.Service class.

This allows our common service initialization code to be
executed.

Closes-Bug: 1366766
Change-Id: I60ed6222a1e9bd54329545767ee329b54876e73a

commit_message:
Mark the Ryu plug-in for Neutron as deprecated as of Juno

Also remove the Ryu plug-in in the list of available network plugin-ins
in the new networking guide to not document a deprecated plug-in.

Change-Id: I289c96b2aa691ccdd7197c2ecdee7697b2428ab5
Closes-Bug: #1356664

commit_message:
Join enabled_ssl_apis array

Adds a stdlib join() to the enabled_ssl_apis so we can specify more than one.

Closes bug: #1360978

Change-Id: Ifd290fea802fc926a9e34076393c2c55c3cd9cf5

commit_message:
Fixed manage_service feature

Using manage_service=>false in class neutron::agents::ovs generates
error. This patch is fixing the issue and makes mentioned use-case
installable.

Change-Id: I5a3205c3e21e1312463f47d938f5854a189c5d38
Closes-bug: #1359823

commit_message:
Use package-installs in more elements

Updates additional elements in diskimage-builder to use the declarative
package install support provided by the package-installs element.
package-installs does not yet support the pkg-map functionality, so
elements using pkg-map are not migrated. That support will come in the
near future.

Change-Id: I3d36adad317ba44326eabd95243d45807e2a8a16

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
Dividing markups into multiple lines

In previous patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/110972/2
markups were put in one lines making them harder to read so I divided
them into multiple lines in order to improve readability.

Change-Id: Ic41c2d522e3de7078cd3d607436780a5179e105d
Closes-Bug: #1355985

commit_message:
Raise descriptive error for over volume quota

If you attempt to create a new instance booting from an image and you
were over your quota on cinder, the nova manager would see that as an
invalid block device. This raises a more descriptive error message in
the logs.

Closes-bug: #1013417
Change-Id: Ie50b97c31580da7fc38c6891d1f3646b91f8aa10

commit_message:
Improve install guide ceilometer controller

I improved the ceilometer controller section in the installation
guide as follows:

1) Renamed file and XML IDs to agree with similar content.
2) Reordered instructions.

Implements: blueprint installation-guide-improvements
Co-Authored-By: Matt Kassawara <mkassawara@gmail.com>

Change-Id: I13644b0d4f244be3018d13f3fb5544287277770c

commit_message:
Fix cluster creation with heat engine

* Check stack on empty status because heat stack status maybe is not set
in DB
* Fix E126 pep8 checks
* Fix E127 pep8 checks

Change-Id: I79627407b6deda77b86bf2ac497fa8fdc172cedb
Closes-bug: #1366941

https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1271331'}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2014-08-21 12:34:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Doug,

The fix that is being reverted here could never really have worked in the first place. Retrying communicate() is not something that must be done. 

The reason is that if the system is operating properly, communicate can NEVER return EINTR. The only way in which this can happen is if the system is operating with greenlet improperly monkey-patched.

Trove had a virtually identical scenario to the one you describe and the real issue was that the test framework had not properly monkey patched greenlet.

The consequence of reverting this change on the other bug you identified is literally that there will be no effect.

We had a similar issue to the one described in that bug where a test would fail sporadically with a similar backtrace (not identical).

The issue there was the following.

One test (call it test A) was not monkey patching execute properly and therefore would guaranteed, fail every time.

Another test (call it test B) was monkey patching execute but failed to un-monkey-patch it.

So long as test A ran on the same thread as test B, and after test B, all was well. However, in the rare case where test A ran on a different thread than test B, the failure occurred.

The correct fix was to (a) make test A properly monkey patch execute, and (b) make test B un monkey patch execute.

After this (proposed here) change is accepted, if we find issues where communicate() returns EINTR (aka EAGAIN) the correct solution is to go look in the test suite and find out why the test that is failing isn't properly monkey patching execute.

It turns out that in the way Trove runs its tests (through testr I believe) there is no way to properly monkey patch greenlet at a sufficiently early stage to make it work. Fixing that is something that I'm still working on.

Hope this clarifies the situation."}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2014-08-26 01:34:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Patch Set 3 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-26 03:51:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

Yes, this was done to address a gate bug, although it looks like that may not be an issue anymore (the failing test was rewritten to not use execute).

That said, retrying on an EAGAIN is the correct behavior IMHO, so I don't think we should be completely ripping out the retry.  From the bug, it appears this was just exposing a legitimate bug in the test case.  Is there any change actually needed here?"}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2014-09-04 17:00:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Ben,

EAGAIN on communicate() is an indication of an incorrect mock. But retrying is never the right solution.

I'm happy not to merge this change, the code is still wrong. IMHO."}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2014-09-04 17:13:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

EAGAIN means that a particular operation couldn't be done right now, but it might work in the future.  The definition of the error even says to try again: http://pubs.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/000095399/basedefs/errno.h.html : "Resource unavailable, try again"'}, {'account_id': 708, 'date': '2014-09-04 17:24:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

We get EAGAIN here from IPC operation (reading from pipe), not from the whole communicate() call. So if (when) we fail to handle EAGAIN in read/write (because of bad monkey-patching), we could repeat just that syscall (which should be done in the lower level by proper monkey-patching), but if we repeat whole command we might get partial result. Part of it will already be read by first communicate() until it drained all buffers and only the last part will be returned as result.

Overall this particular issue (and workaround) would've worked in a very strict subset of cases. In general we shouldn't get EAGAIN here at all, and if we do then we should get at least once for every call."}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2014-09-04 21:59:37.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2014-09-04 22:08:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review+2

Okay, I talked with amrith a bunch about this today, and it turns out EAGAIN should never be raised by communicate in a plain Python environment.  That's just not how communicate works (see discussion on http://bugs.python.org/issue22114).

However, it seems eventlet throws all that out the window, but only when there's some sort of weird incomplete monkey patching going on.  Even then, the retry logic doesn't work because on the second call to communicate stdin has been closed and raises the error in the Closes-Bug from the commit message.

So it sounds like removing the retry is fine.  It never actually worked, and there's a different issue we need to solve.  Note that Nova never would have noticed the retry problems because they rewrote the problematic test to not use processutils at all.  We mostly left the retry loop because at the time it seemed to make sense (EAGAIN -> retry), but evidently that's not the right thing to do either.

Amrith has opened the Related-Bug to track the underlying eventlet problem, but in the meantime it appears removing the retry is the right thing to do."}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2014-09-04 22:10:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

[{'created': '2014-08-15 21:17:18.000000000', 'message': "Handle a failure on communicate()

After much debugging of the subject bug, we've concluded that a
failure and an exception of OSError with EAGAIN from communicate()
indicates some monkey business. In the specific case that we're seeing
in Trove, it is because monkey patching didn't quite get done the way
it should.

In any event, retrying isn't the answer.  This change reverts an
earlier change that retried the communicate() call and instead hurls
the OSError exception back to the caller, if we are out of retries. A
test case to fake the communicate() failure has been amended to ensure
that we handle this in what we believe now to be the right way.

commit_message:
Handle a failure on communicate()

After much debugging of the subject bug, we've concluded that a
failure and an exception of OSError with EAGAIN from communicate()
indicates some monkey business. In the specific case that we're seeing
in Trove, it is because monkey patching didn't quite get done the way
it should.

In any event, retrying isn't the answer.  This change reverts an
earlier change that retried the communicate() call and instead hurls
the OSError exception back to the caller, if we are out of retries. A
test case to fake the communicate() failure has been amended to ensure
that we handle this in what we believe now to be the right way.

Originally-Submitted-In: I2450d2dc425a3d29eaba4d5ff9badc4a992a0ec8

Change-Id: Ie36d77eebb2c20124a61ff6029c3b97bfffb9427
Closes-Bug: #1347337
Related-Bug: #1365736

just doing a bit more testing. it seems there is some degradation in write performance(~5%) when i run against make_test_data.py (something i didn't notice when running against local devstack but that has more load changes due to services)... it make be because of the additional table insert required (also we do hash metadata to allow for it to be comparable).

@Mike, is this consistent with what you'd expected?"}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-08-13 20:22:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12:

additional comments... the performance pendulum swings when there's metadata. if there's no/little metadata the old way is faster by 5-10%... if there's metadata(ie. 5+ attrs), this current method out performs... considering most our samples have some form of metadata, i'm ok for this to be reviewed as is."}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-08-13 20:34:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12:

(4 comments)

hi gordon - 

I added some initial comments about optimizing the creation of the resource object.    Theres a few things that can make it a little bit lighter right off.  More fundamental speed improvements might be a little more involved.  The get-or-create pattern is tricky in that its most simple form is the slowest; usually I try to use one of many techniques to speed it up but they are dependent on how the program works.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-08-13 20:38:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12:

another technique you could use for now regarding that resource metadata would be to use raw insert() for the k/v pairs, see line 5252 of https://review.openstack.org/#/c/113324/2/nova/db/sqlalchemy/api.py for an example of that. this allows it to use an "executemany()" and not go through the effort of retrieving PK identifiers.'}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-08-13 21:24:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12:

(2 comments)

Here are some performance results after testing this patch:
Test environment: Ubuntu 14.04, devstack deployed mysql 5.6 with about 30k samples in the sample table.

Before applying the patch:
Meter-list
   Function do_meter_list took 6.017778 sec (avg=0.120356, min=0.054369, max=0.430959) for 50 iterations ()

Sample-list -m image
   Function do_sample_list took 463.706373 sec (avg=23.185319, min=21.618186, max=24.411665) for 20 iterations 


After Applying the patch:
meter-list:
   Function do_meter_list took 9.818204 sec (avg=0.196364, min=0.118328, max=0.497028) for 50 iterations ()

Sample-list -m image:
   Function do_sample_list took 418.981839 sec (avg=20.949092, min=19.422163, max=22.190503) for 20 iterations   


After applying the patch:
There is about 10% performance gain on sample-list.
And about 50% performance degradation on get meter-list.'}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2014-08-29 22:46:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 24: Code-Review-1

I think we should merge the indexes first (which is a small change) and bring a huge performance boost and then re-evaluate queries changes to squeeze even more performance.'}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-09-01 23:35:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 24:

Srinivas, just for reference... when you say "this patch" are you referring to patchset 24? 

also, as i recall from emails, you mention this patch originally had no effect on meter-list? i'm curious as to what changed? do you know what patchset the original test was run against?'}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-09-02 01:04:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24:

so i just tested patchset 24, on fedora 20 and 5.5.38-MariaDB. i get differing results. when i run meter-list i actually get numbers closer to the same (if not better):

average times (standard deviation is pretty low aside from first get):
meter-list (code as is): 0m0.548s
meter-list (with patch24): 0m0.491s
resource-list (as is): 0m1.870s
resource-list (patch24): 0m0.788s

the way i tested was:
1. ran devstack with master code
2. collected ~10000 samples (9708 to be exact)
3. shut down all services except ceilometer-api (to avoid system load mucking data)
4. ran meter-list, resource-list a few times and averaged
5. took patchset 24, applied migration to collected samples
6. ran meter-list, resource-list a few times and averaged

did you test differently on your end? also, are you using 'real' meters or just randomly generating 30k datapoints? just curious since my times are quite a bit slower than yours and i'm running testing against 1/3 dataset (although i'm just running tests off a laptop)"}, {'account_id': 12637, 'date': '2014-09-02 02:53:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24:

Here is my test environment:

Openstack is setup with devstack
Ubuntu 14.04
Cloud instance 4 core and 8GB
MySql 5.5. For first test with this patch along with cdent's patch (TODO: paste the link)

The first time when I communicated the results, this patch was not tested in isolation, it was combined with cdent's patch that does away with sub query in meter-list. The result for meter-list in the first test also similar in nature. i.e. The performance suffered after the patch is applied.

In the 2nd test results I posted above are tested with similar setup except with Mysql 5.6. The results again are similar in both cases.

The performance tests can vary greatly with different setups, If you want to take a look I can let you access the instance I tested and do your tests. The way our stress tests are done is far from ideal, it should be taken up by a independent team with a agreed upon configuration for testing. Since we don't have that it can lead to some head scratching and confusion."}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-09-02 15:01:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 24:

using above steps, i get less performance gains using postgres 9.3.5 (with just over 10k samples)

meter-list (as is and patch24) no difference considering variance: 0m0.491s

resource-list (as-is): 0m0.917s

resource-list (patch24): 0m0.772s'}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2014-09-02 15:05:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24:

Gordon, MariaDB or Postgres are not the default databases set in Devstack so we shouldn't use them as a guideline for performance improvements. We are testing against a fresh devstack installation that is what the majority of the people will use."}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2014-09-02 15:17:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 24:

If your resource list runs in 0.917s, what is the test run for meter list? .400s of variance is too high if it is comparable to the sample list times.
Also the before and after your test with postgres is still returning nearly a 20% improvement and no degradation.'}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-09-02 15:28:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24:

Fabio, the 0m0.420s value isn't variance, it was the time taken for both master code and with this patch... the variance comment was that the difference in actual average values was not conclusive because of variance (the datapoints overlap)

well postgres is definitely a devstack option (see postgres gate)

i'm not sure what the question is regarding 20% performance boost... i was just stating it's less than what i get in mysql... the performance gain is expected as it was one of the purposes of this patch: 1) improve resource-list 2) minimise data redundancy 3) hopefully get write speed gain (which i believe we do) 4) do not degrade anything else... which this doesn't seem to do in my tests."}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-09-02 17:56:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24:

chris did some performance tests and linked here: https://tank.peermore.com/tanks/cdent-rhat/DatabasePerfTest

it lists the methodology and such. i think it's a good start and we can see if we there's anything we should be tweaking"}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-09-02 19:55:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 24:

Srinivas, thanks so much for lending the system. i gave my patch a try and it looks like i got similar to results to what chris had. that said, i got a much higher level of variance which i assume is because it's running off a VM. 

with index patch and with normalise patch (separately), they both offered ~15% boost in meter-list performance (but again, variance was large)

Fabio/Srinivas, you can verify using the database (ceilogord - created using make_test_data.py but tweaked a bit to create more meters, resources). some notes:

    - you can run your tests by cloning ceilogord db to ceilometer db and running your performance tests
    - only api service is running.
    - my tests were done using "time ceilometer meter-list > nul" i don't believe that should cause much difference compared to ceilorunner.

if you're ok with patch i'd suggest adding your index to this normalised patch and adding you as a co-author... that or make your patch dependent on this patch... please let me know if you have any concerns'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2014-09-02 21:34:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 24:

Srinivas: just for background, the "Co-Authored-By" tag in the commit message has been used before for a number of ceilometer patches in order to share the authorship attribution. It would be well-understood to mean that multiple developers had made a significant contribution to the patch.

So if you're agreeable to it, that might be a sensible course of action, if it cuts down on unnecessary additional migration logic between separate patches.

Cheers,
Eoghan'}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2014-09-03 20:58:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 24: Code-Review+1

Gordon.

commit_message:
normalise resource data

create a table to contain resource specific attributes.
the new resource table will contain:
- id
- resource_id,
- project_id,
- user_id,
- source_id
- resource_metadata
- metadata_hash

we will only capture unique resources (ie. unique ids or metadata)

Closes-Bug: #1320257
Implements: blueprint bigger-data-sql
Co-Authored-By: Srinivas Sakhamuri <srinivas.sakhamuri@hp.com>
Change-Id: I4a32688ad3a78e574e018a154cb145e31da6298e

Document the standard for PaaS service notifications

This spec defines a minimum data set and optional fields to be
included in the notification (header+payload) produced by PaaS
services.

commit_message:
Metadata Definitions Catalog

A common API hosted by the Glance service for vendors, admins,
services, and users to meaningfully define available key / value
pair and tag metadata. The intent is to enable better metadata
collaboration across artifacts,services, and projects for
OpenStack users.

This is about the definition of the available metadata that can
be used on different types of resources (images, artifacts,
volumes, flavors, aggregates, etc). A definition includes the
properties type, its key, it's description, and it's constraints.
This catalog will not store the values for specific instance
properties.

This patch updates the spec to reflect the Juno release.

Change-Id: Idc6b24c8caf5ce07800352ab6f4c5829ec35ca4f
Co-Authored-By: Travis Tripp <travis.tripp@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Lakshmi N Sampath <lakshmi.sampath@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: murali sundar <murali.sundar@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Wayne Okuma <wayne.okuma@hp.com>

commit_message:
Separate existence checks for ca and signing certs

Currently, dummy certificates are generated in generate_certs_into_json
if at least one of KeystoneCACertificate, KeystoneSigningKey or
KeystoneSigningCertificate is not specified in JSON file. This review
separates existence check for KeystoneCACertificate from
KeystoneSigning* checks.

With this review, just external KeystoneCACertificate can be provided,
and os-cloud-config will generate KeystoneSigning certificate and key.
Similar, only KeystoneSigning certificate and key can be provided, and
os-cloud-config will generate dummy KeystoneCACertificate.

Change-Id: I972acaa786a4988f256ba8c4206c11d2b4965d0e

commit_message:
Ironic: don't canonicalize extra_specs data

Don't canonicalize the cpu_arch extra_specs field. This is important
because the scheduler filters which use extra specs don't
canonicalize things either and as such you'll have mismatched fields
causing instances not to get scheduled.

This was recently changed as part of the Ironic -> Nova driver patch
series. We still want to canonicalize supported_instances though...

Change-Id: I9342213b5433113816142b1f737119065e9f077f
Closes-bug: #1366859

commit_message:
require eventlet in RPC service.

Ubuntu 14.04 forces librabbitmq when kombu is used
Unfortunately it forces a version that has a crash
bug.  Calling eventlet.monkey_patch() tells kombu
to use libamqp instead.

Change-Id: I9bc2073f620391e5d0b384142a4d4b0ad7104fcf
Closes-Bug: 1365679

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-10 22:25:01.000000000', 'message': 'Repair pysqlite transaction support

This patch applies the events discussed in
SQLAlchemy documentation at
http://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/rel_0_9/dialects/sqlite.html#serializable-isolation-savepoints-transactional-ddl
which correct for pysqlite's modifications to SQLite's transactional
cycle.   We turn off pysqlite's automatic emit of BEGIN
as well as COMMIT before any DDL, and instead emit our own
BEGIN at the point where SQLAlchemy knows a transaction is to start.
A proof of concept is added to illustrate SAVEPOINT working
completely.

SAVEPOINT support will be needed in order to support
transactional testing with rollbacks inside of tests.

In continuing with the theme of more explicit SQL being
added to engines, thus making it more difficult to
"repurpose" a SQLite engine to behave like other backends,
the test suite within test_exc_filters
has also been modified to not rely upon the full
session.create_engine() process for unit tests, instead
calling upon just those listeners being tested.

Change-Id: Ie39bd2287173327903523b66160653608d9e8652

commit_message:
Repair pysqlite transaction support

This patch applies the events discussed in
SQLAlchemy documentation at
http://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/rel_0_9/dialects/sqlite.html#serializable-isolation-savepoints-transactional-ddl
which correct for pysqlite's modifications to SQLite's transactional
cycle.   We turn off pysqlite's automatic emit of BEGIN
as well as COMMIT before any DDL, and instead emit our own
BEGIN at the point where SQLAlchemy knows a transaction is to start.
A proof of concept is added to illustrate SAVEPOINT working
completely.

SAVEPOINT support will be needed in order to support
transactional testing with rollbacks inside of tests.

Change-Id: Ie39bd2287173327903523b66160653608d9e8652

commit_message:
Translator functions cleanup part 2

This part fixes ironic/drivers folder.

Some modules use _ function for log translation, even when the
translated string is passed to e.g. LOG.warn function. This patch
fixes it, using translator functions appropriate for corresponding
log levels. Translator functions, imported from
ironic.openstack.common.gettextutils are now imported from
ironic.common.i18n. Translator functions are imported the same way
across all modules. All places that are changed conform to
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.i18n/guidelines.html

Partial-bug: #1364813

Change-Id: I77cf2582d2e9173d57da473cba118fd8b48a8735

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-08 16:11:02.000000000', 'message': "Mock glance client object in version unit tests

This patch changes the glance client version unit tests
to mock the Client object completely.  Previously the
tests were ensuring the right version of the client was
returned, but that required too much knowledge of glance's
implementation and ended up breaking the tests when glance
changed the implementation details of the Client class.

The new code tests if cinder is calling the integration
point correctly for the version, rather than if glance

commit_message:
Mock glance client object in version unit tests

This patch changes the glance client version unit tests
to mock the Client object completely.  Previously the
tests were ensuring the right version of the client was
returned, but that required too much knowledge of glance's
implementation and ended up breaking the tests when glance
changed the implementation details of the Client class.

The new code tests if cinder is calling the integration
point correctly for the version, rather than if glance
is correctly returning the right client; that should be
a glance test, not a cinder test.

Closes-Bug: 1366596
(cherry-picked from 04abab869d28e007d9b869122740f70cd839daf7)
(cherry picked from commit 5863f52a9f140cfd13e1794ebf6db434517802b3)

Conflicts:

	cinder/tests/image/test_glance.py

Change-Id: I979175e6c3b5f98076bde6d36ca52fb8b03009b8

commit_message:
ofagent: Remove @author tags and update copyright notices

When writing these modules, ofagent team (kakuma, yamamoto) thought
that @author tag was OpenStack's style to represent authorships.
But it turned out to be wrong.  Acutally there seems to be a consensus
not to use them.  So, replace them back to the original Ryu-style
copyright notices.

Change-Id: Icc9fdd1850c0c1dbd354bb3312199a7f6849925a

commit_message:
Use adapter from keystoneclient

The keystoneclient provides an adapter which maintains the client state
around the session. We should re-use this rather than copy it and it
also means we will get new adapter functions and parameters as they
become available.

Change-Id: I05c0d650dcdd69f7e77a06563d735efe521a41ae

commit_message:
Description clean-up for volume actions

Some minor description clean-ups for volume action
'change volume type' and 'upload to image' to remove
'From here you can'.

Also remove unecessary 'required=True' for the field.

Closes-Bug: #1364623

Change-Id: Ia8c1a593e80abf193f26f7cb97bc1ba383383399

commit_message:
User keystone policy to check if user password can be updated

Keystone have a policy for change password, we need to apply this to
horizon too.

policy:
  "identity:change_password": "rule:admin_or_owner"

Change-Id: Idd35646f9cbe4fadaa96bc85b243ed4f7823d9dd
Closes-bug: 1347354

[{'created': '2014-09-09 00:08:27.000000000', 'message': 'Netapp: fix multiple copies of cinder-volume

Various commands were failing when running multiple copies of
cinder-volume. This is due to storing an in memory copy of the luns
which may get updated in the backend by another cinder-volume. Fix
it by attempting to refresh the list of luns if one is not found
during a request.

Change-Id: Iecd1dc5146525d7240a09f71669a3ab239c488bd
Resolves-bug: #1367044
'}]
commit_message:
Netapp: fix multiple copies of cinder-volume

Various commands were failing when running multiple copies of
cinder-volume. This is due to storing an in memory copy of the luns
which may get updated in the backend by another cinder-volume. Fix
it by attempting to refresh the list of luns if one is not found
during a request.

Change-Id: Iecd1dc5146525d7240a09f71669a3ab239c488bd
Resolves-bug: #1367044

commit_message:
Fix agent PXE template

This regressed when the iLO/agent code landed. This commit:
* Fixes the template
* Adds a test for the agent PXE template
* Removes unused parameter ipa-advertise-url from the template

Change-Id: I41a0189ce5d14e1f1e6b7be9872d029e157fe3c2

[{'created': '2014-07-10 13:03:30.000000000', 'message': 'Add SMB Volume Driver

Introduces a volume driver which makes use of SMB shares for
hosting volumes as disk images, having a similar workflow with
the other NFS like drivers.

The driver uses Samba in order to access the SMB shares. It takes
SMB shares information such as share path, credentials and other
mount flags from a config file of which location can be configured
in the cinder config file.

It includes all the features required by the Juno release.

Implements: blueprint smbfs-volume-driver

Change-Id: I3b4bebf73122d5b784228af18f9b1eddfc02b643

commit_message:
Add SMB Volume Driver

Introduces a volume driver which makes use of SMB shares for
hosting volumes as disk images, having a similar workflow with the
other NFS like drivers.

The driver uses Samba in order to access the SMB shares. It takes
SMB shares information such as share path, credentials and other
mount flags from a config file of which location can be configured
in the cinder config file.

It includes all the features required by the Juno release.

Driver cert results:
http://paste.openstack.org/show/100915/

The online snapshot related tests have been skipped as this
feature is not supported yet.

Implements: blueprint smbfs-volume-driver

DocImpact

Co-Authored-By: Adelina Tuvenie <atuvenie@cloudbasesolutions.com>

Change-Id: I3b4bebf73122d5b784228af18f9b1eddfc02b643

[{'created': '2014-07-16 13:55:34.000000000', 'message': 'Add newly_discovered column to Node object

commit_message:
Add newly_discovered column to Node object

The new field of type boolean will be used to distinguish nodes,
that were just added by auto-discovery process.

Also make sure that this field is unset on unsetting maintenance.

Change-Id: I9e9554c32639f212083fd8c7a58ec45911185ee2
Implements: blueprint generic-hardware-discovery

Remove unnecessary mapping from Agent drivers

Both vendor methods comes from the same VendorInterface, so no need to
use the MixinVendorInterface.

commit_message:
In the Redis driver, only read the msg body when needed

For non-trivial messages, reading the msg body when it isn't necessary
for the business logic can have significant performance implications.

As part of this work, some of the Redis queries were able to be DRYed.

This patch was tested using ZAQAR_TEST_REDIS=1.

Change-Id: I2256404ca9320a22e574625edb229979c1800b40

commit_message:
Small fixes for 'test_autoscaling' Heat test

- Skipped test in HA mode due to native Heat autoscaling
doesn't work in HA
- Increased timeout due to periodic Time Limit Errors in the
system tests

Closes-Bug: #1365431

Hi Nejc,

I been thinking a bit about we might mitigate the complexity in the pipeline.yaml introduced by this change and the earlier addition of the {LB|FW|VPN}aaS discovery 
extensions.

So we already have the concept of a per-agent default discovery extension, which is set via code (as opposed to pipeline config) by the compute agent:

  https://github.com/openstack/ceilometer/blob/master/ceilometer/compute/manager.py#L28

How about we extend this notion to encompass per-pollster default discovery extensions also?

This could be achieved, for example, by adding a new default_discovery property on PollsterBase, set to None in the base class. In the subclasses this property could be overridden as appropriate, to say "endpoint:image" for the image.* pollsters, or to "lb_pools" for the network.services.lb.pools pollster, and so on.

Then in the PollingTask on each poll_and_publish cycle, each of per-pollster discovery extensions could be called *once* upfront *before* the existing per-pollster for loop is entered:

  https://github.com/openstack/ceilometer/blob/master/ceilometer/agent.py#L83

with the per-pollster discovered resources cached for example via a new initial for loop like:

  discovered_per_pollster = {}
  for pollster in self.pollsters:
      if pollster.default_discovery:
          discovered_per_pollster[pollster.name] = self.manager.discover(pollster.default_discovery)

Within that existing for loop, we could add further logic like:

  for pollster in self.pollsters:
      key = pollster.name
      LOG.info(_("Polling pollster %s"), key)
      pollster_resources = discovered_per_pollster[key] # **
      source_resources = list(self.resources[key].resources)
      try:
          samples = list(pollster.obj.get_samples(
              manager=self.manager,
              cache=cache,
              resources=pollster_resources or source_resources or agent_resources, # **
          ))
          publisher(samples)
      ...

(with the changed lines above marked by "# **")

Just riffing ... what do you think of the idea?

Cheers,
Eoghan'}, {'account_id': 8052, 'date': '2014-09-01 09:05:48.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 8052, 'date': '2014-09-01 09:36:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

New approach up, using Eoghan's idea of per-pollster discoveries. Also introduces discovery caching in order not to make redundant API calls to services."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-01 10:48:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

[{'created': '2014-08-29 09:10:03.000000000', 'message': "PoC: Migrate the rest of the central agent pollsters to use discoveries

Currently, not all the central agent pollsters use discoveries.
In order to enable horizontal scaling, all pollsters must use
discoveries so the resources can be partitioned across the pool
of running central agents.

For pollsters that don't poll specific resources, but only poll
general info from services, we treat the service endpoints as
resources. So in the case of glance, there will be only one
resource available for all the pollsters (a glance endpoint).
If there are multiple agents running, only one will be assigned
that endpoint and only one will poll Glance API.

Implements: blueprint central-agent-partitioning

commit_message:
Migrate the rest of the central agent pollsters to use discoveries

Currently, not all the central agent pollsters use discoveries.
In order to enable horizontal scaling, all pollsters must use
discoveries so the resources can be partitioned across the pool
of running central agents.

For pollsters that don't poll specific resources, but only poll
general info from services, we treat the service endpoints as
resources. So in the case of Glance, there will be only one
resource available for all the pollsters (a Glance endpoint).
If there are multiple agents running, only one will be assigned
that endpoint and only one will poll Glance API.

DocImpact
Co-Authored-By: Dina Belova <dbelova@mirantis.com>
Closes-Bug: #1364352

Looks good to me - thanks for picking this up'}, {'account_id': 1921, 'date': '2014-08-07 21:03:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

What we did in the past to allow changes that affect the API such as this one was to wait until the service changes is ready to merge, merge a skip of the test(s) on tempest, merge the service change, re-enable the test.

With branchless tempest, to be able to unskip the test we would need to backport the service change to icehouse, which in my understanding is one of the things that branchless tempest is trying to enforce.

With this proposed change the test would keep working all the time, but we would not enforce the backport, unless after nova merges its change we add the new quota fields to the default set in the test, and we revert to a tighter check.

If this is the planned approach, I'm ok with it, but it it may be easier to use the temporary skip.

I don't think we should keep this in indefinitely, else we would always leave the door open to new quota items being added without tempest noticing it.

I'm leaving a placeholder -1 here, the nova change is still WIP so there should be enough time to clarify this and get other opinions."}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2014-08-07 22:31:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Andrea

Thanks for your review.

 > With branchless tempest, to be able to unskip the test
 > we would need to backport the service change to
 > icehouse, which in my understanding is one of the
 > things that branchless tempest is trying to enforce.
 >
 > With this proposed change the test would keep working
 > all the time, but we would not enforce the backport,
 > unless after nova merges its change we add the new quota
 > fields to the default set in the test, and we revert to
 > a tighter check.

That is a point of this patch. I think we cannot backport
the nova patch of a new quota to stable branch because the
patch is one of new feature, not bug-fixing patch.

As openstack-dev ml discussion[1], we should backport bug-fixing
patches only to stable branches because we need to keep these
branches stable. So that is a reason why this patch allows new
quota types instead of temporary skips.

Related to this topic, there is the other point. After a new
quota is added with the nova patch, how to check it on Tempest.
If adding a new quota definition to Tempest, the test would fail
on stable/icehouse branch. On the other hand, if not adding it,
we cannot check the new quota existence forever. I guess now
we need some Tempest options for passing available quotas and
we need to pass quotas based on the branch. However, now there
is not this kind of options. So I think current patch is the
best in this situation.

[1]: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-July/041416.html'}, {'account_id': 1921, 'date': '2014-08-08 07:36:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

You're absolutely right, this is not a bug-fix and not back-porting material, thanks for pointing it that out.
Still I think the only reason why we have a test in tempest that checks quota against a static list of items is to protect us against unwanted API changes. 
This is of course a wanted one, but the change proposed here opens up the doors new ones. It is unlikely to add a new quota item by mistake, so if the other cores are fine with this so am I.
The alternative would be to have a feature flag that defaults to False. The icehouse devstack would leave it to its default.
The Juno devstack would need a change to set it to true once the nova change is merged."}, {'account_id': 1501, 'date': '2014-08-08 08:27:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

The new quota values will only be visible via the API if the extension os-server-group-quotas is loaded - so a different way to fix the tempest test would be to make is specifically check for that extension when building the list of expected quota values:

Something like:

if extension_is_loaded('os-server-group-quotas'):
     expected.append('server_groups')
     expected.append('server_group_members')

That would be in keeping with the way api extensions are meant to work.

Note that when I've finished the change there will be two new quota values - only one is there at the moment, I hope to get the other one done today"}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2014-08-11 01:31:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

Hi Andrea,

 > Still I think the only reason why we have a test in tempest that checks
 > quota against a static list of items is to protect us against unwanted
 > API changes.
 > This is of course a wanted one, but the change proposed here opens up
 > the doors new ones. It is unlikely to add a new quota item by mistake,
 > so if the other cores are fine with this so am I.

That is a nice point.
This patch should wait for reivews of Nova side. At least, one +2 is necessary
for Nova patch(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/104957/) before this patch is
approved, because we need to pay attensions for REST API changes.
So I will score this as WIP.

 > The alternative would be to have a feature flag that defaults to False.
 > The icehouse devstack would leave it to its default. The Juno devstack
 > would need a change to set it to true once the nova change is merged.

Yea, that is a reasonable idea. On the other hand, Tempest has already contained
some design/direction on the response body verification. The verification denies
the removal of API parameters from a response body, but it allows additional
parameters in a response body. For example, we can see jsonschema definitions
under tempest/api_schema/response/compute/ and they don't contain

  'additionalProperties': False

to avoid blocking Nova API improvements which contain new API parameters."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-11 01:31:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
Allow new quota types

On Nova commit Ib281e43eabfbd176454bde7f0622d46fb04fcb79, we are trying
a new quota type for server groups.
However, current Tempest denies unexpected quota types on its own tests,
and we cannot add the new quota without Tempest changes.
This patch changes quota tests for checking mandatory quota existence
and allowing new quota types.

Change-Id: I4409a7240dc0a3fa1e11c64c5f5a56ca656b70a4

commit_message:
Use oslo.utils instead of ironic.openstack.common

DRAC driver and ISCSI deploy module still use excutils, importutils
and strutils from ironic.openstack.common. Now oslo.utils is used
instead.

Closes-bug: #1366032

commit_message:
Ensure designate-sink has policy initialized

We split the designate Service class into a base Service class,
and a RPCService class.

Service contains code common to every Designate service, while
RPCService contains code for any RPC servers.

Closes-Bug: 1366764
Change-Id: I2410a83c9f4123b2011f4f6409aacb18f010097f

commit_message:
Merge two unittest modules that test same module

For module 'manila.share.manager' exist two test suites located in
manila.tests.test_share and manila.tests.share.test_manager
This commit merges two mentioned test modules to second one, because it is
located properly.

Changes:
- updated Fake driver in 'manila.tests.fake_driver' module to satisfy
  proper driver interface.
- used updated fake driver in result test suite instead of own implementation.
- moved unittests to another module.
- deleted one overlapping test.

This commit does not add new tests, there are still uncovered functionality
exist.

Change-Id: I7c102e1331f267ac43bcb09c4d9fe9426a0d8853
Partial-Bug: #1348633

commit_message:
Minor fixes for ipminative console support

This patch fixed a few minor problems left over from
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/97331/. It added some missing
exceptions in the doc strings. It also fixed a spelling error
in a testcase etc.

Change-Id: Ic8b1903d7ec429abb72999795631a8cbc7da05f5

commit_message:
Update the revocation configuration docs

Since the revocation extension is enabled by default, I think we
can drop it's experimental tag, and replace it with an INFO one
that says it's enabled by default.

Change-Id: If24994287381c1edb1d8b7e947d0661e2980b240

commit_message:
Add version parameter to adapter.

The version parameter was left out of adapter previously because setting
a version number triggers discovery and I felt that it was not ready for
the other services.

However if it isn't set then it won't be used and we may as well
implement it here once rather than have the individual services that do
support it override it themselves.

Change-Id: I707380a01175dc19b59de32cbb8fd2bb123d7335

commit_message:
Add FlavorList.get_by_ids() bulk query operation

This adds a get_by_ids() method to the FlavorList object, which allows fetching
multiple flavors by a list of their ids in a single batch operation.

Related to blueprint virt-driver-numa-placement

Change-Id: If08a16cf3fc7cfdc25e873c6d382a0b4e37ac68d

commit_message:
Decoupling client creation from actual config calls

Client creation should be decoupled from the config calls
and always passed as parameter. Adding deprecation for now
it will be deleted later.

Unification of client creation across all config functions.

Change-Id: I26b1d42fffcd678ca5b40174b3f3ac7fc356c5a4
