[{'created': '2014-08-22 11:23:05.000000000', 'message': "Fix Unicode decode error with Windows AD as identity backend

We can't assume values come from external ldap server are utf8
encoded, an illegal sequence of str characters will cause the
coding-specific decode() to fail.
https://wiki.python.org/moin/UnicodeDecodeError

Change-Id: Ic8c101ca12a1b9c09db14da20030564cc29f9cce
Closes-bug: #1359504
"}, {'created': '2014-09-01 14:39:30.000000000', 'message': "Fix Unicode decode error with Windows AD as identity backend

We can't assume values come from external ldap server are utf8
encoded, an illegal sequence of str characters decode will raise
exception 'utf8' codec can't decode byte. This patch addes 'replace'
option instead of default 'strict' to handle encoding errors.
https://wiki.python.org/moin/UnicodeDecodeError

Change-Id: Ic8c101ca12a1b9c09db14da20030564cc29f9cce
Closes-bug: #1359504
"}]
commit_message:
Fix Unicode decode error with Windows AD as identity backend

We can't assume values come from external ldap server are utf8
encoded, an illegal sequence of str characters decode will raise
exception 'utf8' codec can't decode byte. This patch addes 'replace'
option instead of default 'strict' to handle encoding errors.
https://wiki.python.org/moin/UnicodeDecodeError

Change-Id: Ic8c101ca12a1b9c09db14da20030564cc29f9cce
Closes-bug: #1359504

commit_message:
Remove recursive imports

There was a recursive import between common.transport.wsgi.helpers and
the wsgi.utils module in queues.transport. To avoid future recursions,
we should always keep in `wsgi.utils` things that are specific to
queues. All other utils/helpers should go in `common/transport/wsgi`

Change-Id: I80ad937a2ed8b3ca62392769da16987c21056bc2

commit_message:
Undercloud params for compute driver and manager

Add undercloud template parameters for NovaComputeDriver,
NovaComputeManager, and NovaSchedulerHostManager.

The motivation here is to be able to test configure Nova to use
the new (in-tree) Ironic compute driver (which used to live
in Ironic).

NOTE: The initial Nova in-tree Ironic driver won't have its
own ClusteredComputeManager (compute_manager). Even so I've
gone ahead and added a parameter for NovaComputeManager
so we can modify this accordingly in the future without
making hard coded template changes.

Change-Id: Ib48a6b6d8a6cff157bdf3948bd0330e9b29dd46a

commit_message:
Modify format of granularity string

Previously granularity was in a per-second format
and was called without units.

Modification now requires granularity to be formatted
as an offset string, such as '90S', or '1Min'.

Query syntax:

GET /v1/entity/UUID/measures?aggregation=max&granularity=5S

Change-Id: Ibf6548bd23425807b2033cf4c252095effcff738

commit_message:
Add neutron service tag

Service tags allow to skip the test if required service is not
available. But currently, existing 'network' tag never skips a tagged
test, as it is assumed that nova-network is always available.
There needs to be a way to skip the tests that are Neutron-specific
using the tags.
 - Simply making 'network' tag to skip the test would break existing
tests that do use nova-network;
 - Adding a custom skip check instead of using the tag would create a
duplicate boilerplate.

This patch adds 'neutron' tag that would skip the test if Neutron
is not available.

The downside is that there are now 'network' tag and 'neutron' tag,
which is confusing. One of the tags should be removed if
nova-network deprecation is complete.

Change-Id: I369e5b03c318cfc1b42984a05806c50ec44df490
Partial-Bug: #1333875

Move to oslotest

Start using oslotest, it's not a complete migration from
testtools, but it covers most occurances.

commit_message:
Correct configuration of o-c-c collectors

o-c-c registers it's "collectors" config param as a MultiStrOpt, rather
than a ListOpt. The required configuration file format for this type of
option is:

     [DEFAULT]
     collectors = heat_local
     collectors = ec2
     collectors = ...

Change-Id: I35063c75781f855883b02e1e0438b8cc08475ced

commit_message:
Let oslotest manage the six.move setting for mox

This instruction to set up a move in six for the mox module conflicts
with the one in oslotest. We are trying to use mox3 everywhere, so
remove this instruction and let oslotest handle it.

Imported from the incubator change with the same ID.

Change-Id: I59d5799283233f8411044ddb15c8abfc8850014c

commit_message:
Make pdb debugging of openreviews possible.

This allows dropping into pdb while still using genresults-openreviews
which I found useful.

Change-Id: I2dbd2ce773b097248291c7c0897fa02539f1eddc

commit_message:
Add BSN plugin to agent migration script

Adds the Big Switch plugin to the migration script that creates
the agents table. A recent commit (d3be7b040eaa61a4d0ac617026cf5c9132d3831e)
added it to the agent tables but it missed this one so an error was thrown
during migration when it reached a table that depended on the agents table.

Closes-Bug: #1340405
Change-Id: I90a164a1b632c3794a7f7607f3f1da8f7d7b15db

commit_message:
Minor housekeeping in `stack.sh` and `tools/bash8.py`

- require non-empty function name in the style check
- mention `E020` in the comments
- skip `worlddump.py` when $LOGDIR is not set

Change-Id: Ic9c71cf16496b69c06351ed087d3559d19165204

metadata to decide if config_drive will be applied

DocImpact

'}, {'created': '2014-03-13 01:32:27.000000000', 'message': 'Change the force_config_drive option

Currently Nova decides the config_drive based on user input and compute
node configuration.

We could have a cloud wide option so that all instances will have config
drive enabled and this will make resize and cold migration easier.

We could also consider the image requirement because some image may
require config drive support.

The precedence is: cloud wide option -> user input -> image property ->
compute node option.

We can remove the compute node configuration in future after
we get an good idea on upgrade the compute node.

Closes-Bug: #1285880

DocImpact:
    An new image metadata support added.

Change-Id: Ica32fb078d5440dbcf1251175585d34af9549815
Signed-off-by: Yunhong Jiang <yunhong.jiang@intel.com>
'}, {'created': '2014-04-23 18:22:37.000000000', 'message': 'Support image property for config drive

commit_message:
Support image property for config drive

Currently Nova decides the config_drive based on user input and compute
node configuration. We should also consider the image requirement for
config drive.

Implements: blueprint config-drive-image-property

DocImpact:
    An new image metadata support added.

Change-Id: Ica32fb078d5440dbcf1251175585d34af9549815

commit_message:
Import all neutron modules in autogenerate

For autogenerate db schema containing all db models is needed. This can
be achieved by importing all neutron modules. This patch goes through
all packages and modules within neutron package tree and imports them.

Change-Id: I953da8aab460c2b86bcca0b1f34ae69cde9a847e
Closes-Bug: #1346658

commit_message:
VMware: Disable suds caching

The default cache implementation in suds store pickled objects in a
predictable path in /tmp which could lead to attacks. This patch
turns off suds caching to address this security issue.

Change-Id: I7daaa25a0677004e03896298e9c3026d5c33c6ac
Closes-Bug: #1341954
(cherry picked from commit 6a41fe9c5c98a14a355fa81b41aae2c4b0ce0a7b)

commit_message:
Change v3 flavor_manage API to v2.1

This patch changes v3 flavor_manage API to v2.1 and makes v2 unit tests
share between v2 and v2.1.
This patch removes test_create_flavor_name_with_leading_trailing_whitespace
because v2.1 API contains consistent name rule for whole of API request and
the name which contain spaces at the start/end of name is against the rule.

The differences between v2 and v3 are described on the wiki page
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/NovaAPIv2tov3 .

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I57ca2562cb02ce5a35c4596e4c5a753d1268493f

commit_message:
Add bench-requirements.txt to tox venv

In order to generate docs Sphinx has to import all python modules
in the codebase. Because of that, the bench-requirements dependencies
are needed to build the API reference section in the developers guide.

Change-Id: Ic6f61e049386cd751d787088f49c5a22c91f9254

subject: Remove force_tenant_isolation=True from test that doesn't need it

So I think you've misunderstood the purpose of the force_tenant_isolation flag in the test classes. They are not there to say that tenant_isolation is required to run those tests, but instead to use tenant_isolation as a mechanism to create a test user and tenant when it's required for testing. There are cetain tests, mainly tests around quotas, that require a separate tenant from what's provided in the config file to work. Instead of doing this manually we use the flag to specifiy using the tenant isolation mechanism to this. The alternative would be to implement what is essentially tenant_isolation manually for each of those test classes. The flag should only ever be used on tests that require admin which means that tenant_isolation can be used even if it's disabled in the config.

So I'm -2 here, because it breaks the intent of having that attr, and this change will cause is tests to be skipped when there is no cause to do so."}, {'account_id': 9194, 'date': '2014-07-25 15:35:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-25 15:35:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

commit_message:
Fix openSUSE kernel/initrd detection

For some of the scripts, the unversioned name is not
good enough. so determine the link target of "vmlinuz" and
"initrd" to get the full versioned path.

Change-Id: I52f9b5435fafaf7925e2332058a9e41b26478f1c

commit_message:
Increase default RAM for 32bit to 2.5G

After merging patches which include pacemaker and corosync services
in undercloud and overcloud, VMs may run out of memory quite often.
Increasing default memory to 2.5G should make situation more stable.

Change-Id: Ib68a5d542620fadd2b93b87bf8b59115f4d7423c

Minor doc correction in devtest_overcloud.sh

not updated when the Heat stack became the source of the information.

[{'created': '2014-08-15 21:01:42.000000000', 'message': "Log stdout, stderr and command on execute() error

It would help debugging considerably if a failure in execute()
generated a message (at a client specified logging level). Such a
message, generated by execute() would only occur if the user requested
it by specifying a parameter (log_errors), and execute() were to throw
an exception. As an example, this change would address the issue being
addressed in bug 1340124 for the Trove project only.

DocImpact: New parameter added to processutils.execute().  The
possible values of the log_errors parameter are 'all' or 'final'. The
default value of None implies no logging. If it is set to 'final',
stdout and stderr are logged on the final failure. If it is set to
'all', stdout and stderr are logged on every failure.

Change-Id: Id9e94bd8d009b8f134f0b681da5dec5717d662ff
DocImpact:
Closes-Bug: #1342857
Suggested-By: Peter Stachowski <peter@tesora.com>

commit_message:
Log stdout, stderr and command on execute() error

It would help debugging considerably if a failure in execute()
generated a message (at a client specified logging level). Such a
message, generated by execute() would only occur if the user requested
it by specifying a parameter (log_errors), and execute() were to throw
an exception. As an example, this change would address the issue being
addressed in bug 1340124 for the Trove project only.

DocImpact: New parameter added to processutils.execute().  The
possible values of the log_errors parameter are 'all' or 'final'. The
default value of None implies no logging. If it is set to 'final',
stdout and stderr are logged on the final failure. If it is set to
'all', stdout and stderr are logged on every failure.

Originally-submitted-in: If8180e042e1a05374ef705f5873cc0981243619f

Change-Id: Id9e94bd8d009b8f134f0b681da5dec5717d662ff
DocImpact:
Closes-Bug: #1342857
Suggested-By: Peter Stachowski <peter@tesora.com>
Reported-By: Ionu Arrii <iartarisi@suse.cz>

keystone/exceptions.py: Explicitly import the '_' function

This also includes a needed backport of
f9e98e5eb942b22f8db269b2fa3d4fc9e040750e .

Change-Id: Ia9513af6ef123295b60eff597c85864a92552912
Closes-Bug: #1309059

commit_message:
Fix variable passed to driver module

If a create project request is sent to keystone with no enabled field set,
the default behavior should be to set enabled to True for the new project,
but because we are passing the wrong variable to the driver creation
method, this new project end up with the enabled field set to "nothing".

Closes-Bug: #1261976
Change-Id: I9ebfdde03c0f25cadd1323de9863a230d8058f4e
(cherry picked from commit 22301d95142a30e9ec7fb1bde47dc0d0b4eabd9d)

I see. In usual if we mock client.Client with autospec=True we should/can check if valid arguments are passed.
However, we cannot do this. it is not because Client is mocked, but because neutronclient implementation is not a good one. neutronclient.v2_0.client.Client.__init__ take variable keyword arguments (kwargs), so autospecing does not work. IMO, we should specify explicit parameter specification for v2_0.client.Client, and metaplugin tests should use autospec.

Use region_name instead of auth_region.

commit_message:
Translator functions cleanup part 1

This part fixes ironic/common folder and tox.ini file.

Some modules use _ function for log translation, even when the
translated string is passed to e.g. LOG.warn function. This patch
fixes it, using translator functions appropriate for corresponding
log levels. Translator functions, imported from
ironic.openstack.common.gettextutils are now imported from
ironic.common.i18n. Translator functions are imported the same way
across all modules. All places that are changed conform to
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.i18n/guidelines.html

Partial-bug: #1364813

Change-Id: I195d0e256c5412d6d75d2e6c35b19b44f2a0b09f

commit_message:
Add serializers to scheduler call

 * For some purposes, we should able to pass typed
   object as one of method arguments to Scheduler.
   For doing that, we pass serializer for this argument -
   it will be serialized during save to the DB and
   will be deserialized during delayed method call.

Change-Id: I5b4f4f3638d09888b331c29bba9c095163d62288

commit_message:
Refactoring engine to build and call task policies

* Fixed engine to build and call policies
* Fixed policy interface
* Added stubs for wait-before, wait-after and retry policies
* Added factory methods to build policy instances from specification
* Unit tests

Change-Id: I96ad4a80e3f205a81efe2076da4a5db849fc6b75

commit_message:
tests/service: consolidate setUp/tearDown logic

Consolidate the duplicate code for extension api tests.
This will be also used by servicevm extensions later.

At the same time, a bug in test_extension_firewall.py is also fixed.
double call of super().setUp().

Conflicts:
	neutron/tests/unit/services/loadbalancer/test_loadbalancer_plugin.py

Additional changes:
- test_extension_firewall.py: removed unused 'webtest' import

Closes-bug: #1275654
Change-Id: I72f185ef6e5af55729ced51fc0b72fae799d46ac
(cherry picked from commit fdbaba877f98bf20c1ff71c9bd0d04956120f845)

commit_message:
Call setup once in unit tests

Calling it twice will cause testtools to fail.
This applies to load balancer, vpn, and firewall unit tests.

commit_message:
Pin testtools version to < 0.9.36

New testtools require that setUp() is not called twice, and we have
multiple projects that do that. So pin the version for now until we
clear the mess.

Change-Id: I7bbb59534382c9fe39789bbf7d12e14bba41aec0

This avoids resetting the channel where there are no consumers. For
publishing there is no real state associated with the channel so
reusing is fine. Connections tend to be used for one or other of

Change-Id: I297212f1ca7babd127ae33cc7a62bbe23cb70242

commit_message:
Possible performance optimisation for publish

This avoids resetting the channel where there are no consumers. For
publishing there is no real state associated with the channel so
reusing is fine. Connections tend to be used for one or other of
sending or receiving, so this seems like a simple yet potentially
effective patch.

Change-Id: I297212f1ca7babd127ae33cc7a62bbe23cb70242

[{'created': '2014-09-04 17:59:38.000000000', 'message': "Fix tests with testtools>=0.9.39

'rpc_backend' config option in
ceilometer.openstack.common.rpc.__init__.py defaults to
'%s.impl_kombu' % __package__. Because the RPC module is imported
in some other files as ceilometer.openstack.common.rpc, rpc_backend
is set to 'ceilometer.openstack.common.rpc.impl_kombu'. But when
the test loader tries to import the RPC module as openstack.common.rpc
(since it is starting inside the ceilometer folder), registering the
option fails, because we try to register a different default value.

The issue surfaced because testtools==0.9.39 started checking __init__.py
files as well. It is fixed by passing a top-level directory parameter to
the test discovery process.

Change-Id: I08036b54def3eb496772bcf183927b9f70bb7a86
Closes-bug: #1365613
"}]
commit_message:
Fix tests with testtools>=0.9.39

'rpc_backend' config option in
ceilometer.openstack.common.rpc.__init__.py defaults to
'%s.impl_kombu' % __package__. Because the RPC module is imported
in some other files as ceilometer.openstack.common.rpc, rpc_backend
is set to 'ceilometer.openstack.common.rpc.impl_kombu'. But when
the test loader tries to import the RPC module as openstack.common.rpc
(since it is starting inside the ceilometer folder), registering the
option fails, because we try to register a different default value.

The issue surfaced because testtools==0.9.39 started checking __init__.py
files as well. It is fixed by passing a top-level directory parameter to
the test discovery process.

[{'account_id': 7661, 'date': '2014-08-20 20:37:53.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 7661, 'date': '2014-08-20 20:56:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Just to add some context, this has mainly been a problem on ext4 when there are enough containers to cause the container-replicator to run continuously, which isn't all that many on a single spindle storage node.  Anyhow, the updates generate unnecessary sql journal activity which in turn generate a lot of jbd2 (the ext4 journal daemon) writes.

One should probably verify ALL db activity is really necessary or at least on very infrequent code paths.  Lots of needless updates with the replicator turns into too much."}, {'account_id': 7479, 'date': '2014-08-20 21:21:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Make some sqlite UPDATE calls only to records that have changed

Just to add some context, this has mainly been a problem on ext4
when there are enough containers to cause the container-replicator
to run continuously, which isn't all that many on a single
spindle storage node. Anyhow, the updates generate unnecessary
sql journal activity which in turn generate a lot of jbd2
(the ext4 journal daemon) writes.

Related-Bug: 1332025
Change-Id: I057a5f8971f06171ed966505e3b5092324f16ec9

I'm not trying to downplay moving from Icehouse to Juno as being easy or trivial. I'm just wondering if fixing the documentation is sufficient as this is a relatively minor user-experience issue (if no one asks for filtering on email it wont error, and documentation wont claim you can filter on email).

It is obviously better to report clean errors and not have tracebacks. I'm happy to accept this if it really makes QOL better, but if it's not common / real QOL difference it should be fine to leave this as a Juno only fix.

So in short, is it a real win for quality of life/user experience using keystone? If so, I agree it should be backported."}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2014-08-31 20:29:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
No longer allow listing users by email

As specified in the bug description, the listing of users by using the
email attribute as a filter would cause an exception. This is because
the email is not a first class attribute, yet it was considered so in
the filters. Thus, this fix will prevent the exception while also
preventing the filtering by email.

Change-Id: Ibf4b51a91c1e47e8197af49855307460559a7fc9
Closes-Bug: #1306835
(cherry picked from commit 75cca803739a5b4ef197666589582802c7391e17)

Abishek, could you resume the work? Juno-3 milestone already started and it is time to resume. We need several rounds reviews and would not like to rush in the last minutes.

For implementation detail, I have a suggestion. Copied from the blueprint whiteboard. -1 is from the below.

There is a constraint for combinations of ipv6-address-mode and ipv6-ra-mode. It is described in the neutron spec document: http://docs-draft.openstack.org/11/102411/5/gate/gate-neutron-specs-docs/7419e32/doc/build/html/specs/juno/ipv6-radvd-ra.html
Considering this constraint, it seems better to have pull-down menu to select a combo of ipv6-address-mode and ipv6-ra-mode rather than having pull-down menus for two IPv6 mode separately. It contributes to reduce user confusions.

In addition, we need to have good description for IPv6 two modes (RA mode and address mode) because it is not easy to understand for normal cloud users (IMO only network admin familiar with IPv6 can understand the current description in neutron-spec.)'}, {'account_id': 6620, 'date': '2014-07-30 17:14:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Akihiro, YEs I will resume work on this immediately. I did note that it came up in the IPv6 meeting yesterday. I think the neutron support is complete now, I just need to double check that the subnet node discussion is complete and that they are still the same two. But yes I will send out a new patch within the next few days. I think there's a little work to be completed in the edit subnet part and also in the UT part."}, {'account_id': 6620, 'date': '2014-08-04 15:43:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Akihiro, I've just resumed work on this. Reading your comment again, I'm not entirely sure I agree with the single drop down menu for the different options. I agree there are many combinations which work and some which are invalid combinations, and only someone familiar with the IPv6 combinations will know which to make. But isn't that the same case for setting up the options via CLI as well? We could definitely do with a better description message yes, but the description cannot entail all valid combinations. It can maybe provide a pointer to where that can be found? Additionally, if we had a single drop down menu, then for editing also we would need a single drop down menu, no? I also believe, the parameters need to be passed to neutron separately though. That is going to be a little tough to obtain from one single drop down. It is doable but not straightforward."}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2014-08-06 18:11:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Abishek,
Thanks for digging into the detail.

First of all, the dashboard is used by more folks than CLI by users not familiar with the detail, so simpler menu without confusion is more important than the case of CLI. This is the difference between Horizon and CLI and is the reason I proposed the single drop-down menu.

You said only someone familiar with the IPv6 combinations will know which to make. What options should users choose? I cant believe many users are familiar with IPv6 and most users cannot understand what they should select. If the default combination works (None, None; both not specified) for most users/deployments it is good. If the desirable default combination varies across deployments, it is not good.

I understand that users do not need to specify IPv6 address and RA modes, but what I am not sure is this works for all cases with IPv6 subnet. Is there cases where deployers want to configure the default values for IPv6 two modes?

Could you talk with IPv6 Neutron folks about what is better for users not familiar with IPv6?

If my above concerns are unnecessary, two checkboxes looks good.

In addition, IPv6 address and RA modes are placed in the second tab (Subnet required tab). According to your comment, at least they should be placed in Subnet Details tab.

Honestly speaking I am not confident that I can select appropriate combination even after I reviewed some of IPv6 related patches.'}, {'account_id': 6620, 'date': '2014-08-11 14:57:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: -Workflow

Restoring change since neutron initial support has made it through. I need to update tests, but re-opening this to address implementation comments.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-11 14:58:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

(4 comments)

Thanks for the patch! I agree with Akihiro's comments that this looks very complicated for beginner users (a.k.a. me :-)) and it's concerning as well if someone familiar with Neutron who's read the Neutron patches is not confident he could choose a working option. I would favour the comments on the review here and on the blueprint that suggest simplifying the current options, and that very advanced users are more likely to use the CLI. If the simplification is better achieved with a single drop-down, so be it. It doesn't need to have every possible option either. I still wouldn't really know what to choose though. Is there a default option that is most likely to work, without the user having to research how the OpenStack deployment is configured? If a user goal is simply "I want my VM to have an IPv6", how can they do that?

If you feel strongly about allowing users to configure all options, maybe later on we can bring in the UX team to figure out a way to do it in a sane way that's more understandable for regular users... In general though, the dashboard aims toward making things easier to use and understand and hiding complexity. I remember talks of having 2 interfaces, for beginners and for experts... but we're quite far from there currently :) The Neutron stuff is quite complicated for many folks in general, I think we should put our effort to make it more approachable in general.

I hope that makes sense!'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2014-08-27 15:16:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

(1 comment)

Abishek,

As you already now, I implemented the feature in a different way I suggested in the comment: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/115739/.

Can we discuss what option is better and ask open questions to users not familiar with the IPv6 feature? Both patches achieve the same.

There are two points I concern with your approach:

- (a) Usability perspective: whether normal cloud users can understand the option or not. I don't see good explanation on what *EACH* option means so far.
- (b) Implementation perspective: there are too many forms to achieve conditional selection. IMHO five forms for only two attributes looks something wrong even though it works.

We don't have enough time now until Sep 4."}, {'account_id': 4978, 'date': '2014-08-27 15:51:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

I left a few comments on the other patch, I also prefer the 2nd approach with the single drop-down. The longer descriptions in the dropdown give users a better fighting chance to understand what is happening. Moving the options to the details tab makes sense as well since it does not seem to be as essential and basic as the other information in the "Subnet" tab.

Hopefully we can also provide a reasonable default value. Is "None" the same as what we had before that feature was added?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-28 20:05:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified-1

commit_message:
Support new IPv6 subnet modes in Neutron

This addresses addition of two new IPv6 subnet modes
called IPv6_RA_mode and IPv6_address_mode options in Neutron
at the time of creating an IPv6 subnet.

There are fixed values for both these modes.
They can be set to no_attribute_value or one of - slaac,
dhcpv6_stateful or dhcpv6_stateless.

These values represent how Router Advertisements (RAs) are
made for IPv6 address Neighbor discovery for VMs.

Co-Authored-By: Akihiro Motoki <motoki@da.jp.nec.com>
Implements: blueprint neutron-subnet-mode-support
Change-Id: I97abd3642b7da94cda85425534d934f30feb86d2

commit_message:
Change rpc_backend for cinder controller and node

I changed the 'rpc_backend' configuration key for cinder
controller and storage node to use the short version supported
by oslo. Will address Juno version in separate patch.

Change-Id: Ia942e31ce3a8c0508e2b41a4ecee87586478e392
Partial-Bug: #1358752

Sean, the IPA work we're doing in devstack here is to enable us to run gate jobs in IPA and Ironic, both with building from source and downloading the master branch tarball. There's three patches left to land, including this one. The other two are:
- https://review.openstack.org/#/c/114408/
- https://review.openstack.org/#/c/112693/

Once those land, changes to the build scripts (which is what caused this issue) will cause our gate jobs to fail, and won't be landed."}, {'account_id': 10342, 'date': '2014-09-02 15:32:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Sean,

There is a little bit of sensibility to the paths even if they don't make sense at first:

imagebuild/ contains directories that can build IPA images. The only one currently implemented is CoreOS, in imagebuild/coreos. Building the CoreOS image outputs the image to imagebuild/coreos/UPLOAD/ (which was initially chosen to indicate that contained the image to upload).

If this were to change, it would break our check because it would break devstack."}, {'account_id': 10342, 'date': '2014-09-02 15:33:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 10342, 'date': '2014-09-02 15:34:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 10342, 'date': '2014-09-02 15:34:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Simplify ironic-python-agent download

The kernel and ramdisk for IPA are now uploaded separately, this
commit simplifies the download by downloading them separately.

Change-Id: I630b0a9c3d1179a6b97754f1474f62ae7da068a5

commit_message:
Add migrate_data keyword arg to driver destroy()

This patch prepares ironic for the following nova change:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/91722/ by adding the migrate_data
keyword argument that defaults to None.

Change-Id: Ie545181486d3826d2b9a006a523f052561fa46ff

commit_message:
CRUD grant functions don't check user_id and group_id

CRUD grant functions don't check if user_id and group_id exists.
role_id, domain_id, and project_id are checked, and this change
adds checking for user_id and group_id.

This issue could raise an unexpected exception caused by
an unexisting user or group.

Change-Id: I4d8d35f381271d4ffa3b682062dd038e2a360073
Closes-Bug: #1343932

commit_message:
Drop all direct usage of systemctl enable

Since we already have a wrapper script for enabling services called
os-svc-enable, drop all direct usage of systemctl enable, replacing
it with os-svc-enable.

Also drive-by replacements of == with =. == is a pattern match.

Change-Id: I707bf6f02207308e8f61caff17a27b0697096359

This patch intends to fix some small nits introduced along with
the Nova console log patch.

The size of the console log can get bigger than expected because
of a small nit when checking the existing log file size as well
as a wrong size constant.

The method which gets the serial port pipe at the moment returns
a list which contains at most one element being the actual pipe
path. In order to avoid confusion this should return the pipe path

Closes-Bug: #1363899
'}]
commit_message:
Fixes HyperV VM Console Log

This patch intends to fix some small nits introduced along with
the Nova console log patch.

The size of the console log can get bigger than expected because
of a small nit when checking the existing log file size as well
as a wrong size constant.

The method which gets the serial port pipe at the moment returns
a list which contains at most one element being the actual pipe
path. In order to avoid confusion this should return the pipe path
or None instead of a list.

Change-Id: I34e7203716efef8002d463fe6789b36f66ccf535
Closes-Bug: #1363899

commit_message:
Use ipv6 subnet with /64 prefix in ipv6 network API test

SLAAC address mode for ipv6 subnet requires /64 prefix in order to
function properly, so set cidr for the ipv6 subnet explicitly.

Change-Id: I3f0c2a6aee41291e89b0835081e8c7ebcc2c9f04
Closes-Bug: #1361140
Related-Bug: #1357084

commit_message:
Mock glance client object in version unit tests

This patch changes the glance client version unit tests
to mock the Client object completely.  Previously the
tests were ensuring the right version of the client was
returned, but that required too much knowledge of glance's
implementation and ended up breaking the tests when glance
changed the implementation details of the Client class.

The new code tests if cinder is calling the integration
point correctly for the version, rather than if glance
is correctly returning the right client; that should be
a glance test, not a cinder test.

Closes-Bug: 1366596
Change-Id: I979175e6c3b5f98076bde6d36ca52fb8b03009b8
(cherry-picked from 04abab869d28e007d9b869122740f70cd839daf7)

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-19 07:24:04.000000000', 'message': "Change v3 security_groups API to v2.1

This patch changes v3 security_groups API to v2.1 and makes v2 unit tests
share between v2 and v2.1.
This patch doesn't revert /os-security-groups, /os-security-group-rules
and /servers/server_id/os-security-groups because these features are
implemented in Networking API. On v2.1 API, we decide we don't need to
implement proxying features.

The differences between v2 and v3 are described on the wiki page
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/NovaAPIv2tov3 .

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I82660fd514d041bdd1fad0e689fa4fe90d441c47

commit_message:
Change v3 security_groups API to v2.1

This patch changes v3 security_groups API to v2.1 and makes v2 unit tests
share between v2 and v2.1.
This patch doesn't revert /os-security-groups, /os-security-group-rules
and /servers/server_id/os-security-groups because these features are
implemented in Networking API. On v2.1 API, we decide we don't need to
implement proxying features.

The differences between v2 and v3 are described on the wiki page
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/NovaAPIv2tov3 .

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I82660fd514d041bdd1fad0e689fa4fe90d441c47

commit_message:
Add characterization test for group role assignment listing

There was no test that shows what happens when a group assignment is
created and the role assignments are listed (for all backends). The
LDAP assignment backend works incorrectly in that it returns user
assignments for group assignments.

Change-Id: I69bc3501cc5eae3039d805ed006821d6927f0440
Partial-Bug: #1365787

commit_message:
Print only xml files for --print-unused-files

The command openstack-doc-tools --check-build --print-unused-files
only handles .xml files but no other dependencies, so output only
.xml files.

Change-Id: I6c39446cb38ca6e73e3b75597a4e38c49bb56ac7

commit_message:
wrapper: clean the source dir before a checkout

Git doesn't clear folders containing untracked files when switching to
another branch. The autohelp script uses invalid .pyc files when such
switches happen in the diff_branches.py script. This change removes all
the .pyc files before a checkout to avoid this problem.

Change-Id: I0acd0308a3651b27d158546036de5cb0b42d974c

commit_message:
Fix response body format of orchestration_client to dict

'create_stack' function in orchestration_client return raw json strings.
However, in most of cases, raw json strings are not expected because it's
too hard to use. So we should do 'json.loads(body)' for the response body.
And the other apis such as {update,delete,suspend,resume} do not return a
response body in the API spec docs[1]. So we do not need to add
'json.load(body)' to the functions for now.

[1] http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-orchestration-v1.html

Change-Id: Ic7d37d70aa0373d9bbf3ad302d1a521f5adaafe9

commit_message:
Fix git checkout

If the branch does not exist locally, create it properly.
Otherwise the script will abort with freshly checkout sources.

Change-Id: I05960ed862fa61f3c9435f6749d941128812887b
